04172nam a22006735i 9781442662452DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182013onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426624527 a10.3138/97814426624522doi  a(DE-B1597)497167  a(OCoLC)1078911511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aEDU0020002bisacsh04a374.0084/62231 aHeydon, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLearning at the Ends of Life :bChildren, Elders, and Literacies in Intergenerational Curricula /cRachel Heydon. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Introduction to Intergenerational Learning Programs -- tChapter Two. Who Can Say What Is in My Heart? Illustrations of What Intergenerational Learning Programs Have Meant to Their Participants -- tChapter Three. Cases of the Building and Maintaining of Intergenerational Shared-Site Programs -- tChapter Four. Literacy Learning Opportunities in Intergenerational Curricula -- tChapter Five. Opportunities Created by a Semiotic Chain in an Intergenerational Art Curriculum -- tChapter Six. Living, Death, and Dying in Intergenerational Learning Programs -- tChapter Seven. The Lessons of Intergenerational Learning Curricula -- tAppendices -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIntergenerational learning programs bring together skipped generations (for instance, elders and young children) to promote expansive communication and identity options for participants, as well as the forging of relationships between generations. More specifically, these programs help foster multimodal literacy for both generations, encouraging new ways of seeing oneself and the world. Learning at the Ends of Life illustrates the unique benefits of these trail-blazing programs through more than seven years of research on developing and implementing intergenerational curricula in Canada and the United States.The first formal and sustained work on intergenerational curricula and literacies, Learning at the Ends of Life details the experiences of educators and participants in these programs. Rachel M. Heydon brings to life the particular possibilities of arts-based, multimodal curricula that draw on participants’ existing funds of knowledge and interests. Providing practical suggestions for pedagogies and curricula, Heydon helps educators rethink what is taken for granted in monogenerational learning sites and see new possibilities for learners and themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEducationxCurricula. 0aEducation. 0aOlder peoplexEducationxCurricula. 0aOlder peoplexEducation. 7aEDUCATION / Adult & Continuing Education.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266245240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662452.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK